A note of caution from someone who owned and used just about every major Blackberry model: if you already own a standard USB 2.0 cable and you don't need an extra, then you do NOT need this cable. All a Blackberry needs for data transfer is a STANDARD USB 2.0 cable with a Micro-USB connector at one end.There is NOTHING special about this cable and nothing justifies the artificially inflated MSRP listed for it. While this item is sold at a 90% off the MSRP discount, it's probably okay to purchase one, for as long as, after reading the first paragraph you decide that you will need a USB 2.0 cable.The items has 2 stars taken away for the exaggerated marketing claim (professional grade custom cable) and for the inflated MSRP.NOTE: Please make sure that you buy cable with a MICRO-USB connector because this is what your Blackberry needs.
summary: Generic USB 2.0 cable, will work with a Blackberry

I have wanted one of these machines for two years. I finally got a great deal on it at Amazon, and snapped it up. Within three days, I had bought the ingredients needed to make strawberry ice cream and couldn't wait to get started.Unfortunately, the instructions are incorrect when it comes to telling you how long to freeze the bowl. It says that you can freeze it for 6-22 hours, or until you shake the bowl and can't hear any liquid sloshing around. So, I froze the bowl for 6 hours and sure enough, no sloshing. But, this is simply not enough! My strawberry ice cream tasted wonderful, but in the machine never made it past a thick liquid stage. I had to put it in the freezer for hours to get it hard enough to eat. The texture suffered, but the flavor was still great.The next time I made ice cream, I froze the bowl for two days while I was out of town. I got some really great Kaluha ice cream out of it, and I've bought a second bowl so I'll always have one ready to make frozen treats.When used correctly, this ice cream maker is wonderful! reviewText: First let me qualify my comments.  If you are looking for an all purpose ePad or IPAD alternative, buy another product!  That's clearly not what Barnes and Noble designed this unit for.  It's not intended to surf the web, check email, etc.  It is an eReader...PERIOD!Having said that, in my opinion, it is the best out there right now.  It is incredibly light weight - much lighter than even a typical paperback.  It is easy on the eyes for extended reading periods and can be read in basically every lighting situation you could read a real book.  The clarity is sharp but not overpowering on the eyes like an LCD type display is after a few hours.The battery life is insane.  If you turn off WIFI, which should be normal unless you are looking for another book, the battery doesn't need recharging for weeks on end.  Page turning is a simple touch to the left or right of the screen.  Assignable buttons are also provided for pagination but they require a rather firm press.  I found most of the time I don't use them.It has a very responsive touch screen for all your navigation.  I had a 1st generation Nook and this one is far easier to navigate through books which is a big plus for Bibles or Reference books.  It reads ePub format so more than half of what I read comes from the public library.It is not going to be great for color magazines and so on.  You will need a Nook Color or an ePad like Xoom or IPAD for that.  But the downside with those is that the LCD type display cannot be read in direct sunlight so good luck at the beach or pool.One nice feature I use now and then is the dictionary.  If you come across a word you are unfamiliar with you just touch it and up pops an option look it up.  I think Barnes and Noble has a winner here.

This pack has issues with both the design and the construction/materials.I got one of these and also a 4000 series for some overnights in the Adirondacks.The design issues have to do with the way the detachable top bag and the straps fit, really I think they tried to hit a "feature checklist" and ended up without the usability really being as good as one would hope.  Far too much inconvenience having to undo straps to get to pockets, etc., to be really ergonomic.The materials/construction issues have already hit BOTH packs- and I haven't even gone on the hike yet!!!The 5200, the hem ripped off the water-bottle pocket when I was holding it to push the bottle down further.  The stitching was just too close to the edge of the material, and the border just tore right off.  The 4000, one of the buckles just shattered when I was tightening a strap over the rolled-up sleeping pad.  Clearly not nylon, some kind of more fragile plastic.So, I guess you get what you pay for... maybe these are still a good choice if you just can't afford the higher-end brands... a shame, as some skimping on ergonomic thought, careful construction, and good materials could I think have made these good packs.  But I'll probably end up with these both just being 'take a loss' territory.  I don't want buckles to snap in the wilderness, or seams/hems/borders to just rip off hours from my car!!!
summary: Really wanted to like this, but...

reviewText: Unfortunately I can only confirm the majority of the reviews here. While good in concept, this is a poor quality toy. The cardboard pieces may be advertised as "sturdy laminated paper on board construction" but they rip easily. Very easily, even with gentle and proper play by age-appropriate children. Also, the scale of the pieces is smaller than you might think.We purchased ours through Land of Nod but it is the same exact Painter's Palette set. I have not yet asked the manufacturer (Mudpuppy) for a replacement but will be sure to update any resolution here if I do.*I will rate 2 stars because somehow the kids still play with this--even though almost all of the pieces have been broken in half, there are still some slots for fitting together--and because encouraging creative building is to be commended. But ultimately, and if I had it to do over again, I would have purchased the similar-in-concept but better-in-execution set from Pottery Barn Kids. It was made of wood and larger in scale, and cost (I think) forty-nine dollars.* UPDATE *September 22The company sent me a refund check even though I said more than once that I would be happy to receive the "new and improved" set. My guess is they knew the new set would break just as easily (if there even *is* a new set). Still, I appreciate the refund. But I wouldn't recommend this product.September 15I have spoken with the President of the company and am sending some representative broken pieces to him for their production team to review. He says the set has been improved but we'll see.
summary: Cheaply made pieces will break the first time your kid plays with them.

reviewText: I bought this for my son for Halloween.  It was fine for that purpose, but after 2 wearings (for school parade and Halloween night), it was pulling apart at the seams and had a few pulls in the fabric - and my son is not someone who is hard on clothes.  I had only spent $12 on it so it didn't bother me too much, but I would have been upset if I had spent over $15 on it though.  If you are just looking for a cheap Spiderman costume, this will do.  But if you are looking for something for you child to play dress-up in for months to come, invest in something more durable!The costume also tends to run small.  My son is on the big side and at age 3 1/2 it JUST fit (he normally wears a size 4/5).  If you will be wearing bulky clothes underneath for trick-or-treating or if you just have a bigger kid, then consider getting the next larger size.So in summary:  Great for one-time use, NOT so great for long-term play.
summary: Good for a one-time use but not very durable

reviewText: Apple AirPort Express with Air Tunes worked absolutely beautifully for me... until it died.  It was easy to set up, just plug it in, set up using my powerbook's airport utility(I run lots of PCs and a mac at home), and was very reliable unlike few of other wi-fi stations I have used that caused some pain to setup and use.  So up to this point this is a 5 star item.And then here's the problem that is -2 stars.  Just a month or so after my warranty ran out, it suddenly died.  No lights, no power, no nothing, dead.  So I google for it and I find out that there are more than 800 "reported" dead airport express stations just after warranty just like mine.  I do some more research and I find out that its a cheap powerboard apple used that blows fuse and stops working(plus no ventilation but its the quality of the powerboard that's the main problem.)  I don't know what apple was thinking because I always regarded apple as a high quality brand and I am happy with all my other apple products, and was with this one as well until it failed me.This is a good product but just keep in mind that it might die out on you just after warranty, maybe you'll be lucky and it won't die but that cheap powerboard inside won't last forever.
summary: Performance 5 stars, but short life span syndrom ate the 2.

I like these bands a lot! They are great construction quality and they are quite inexpensive as compared to some competing products in the same quality category.I owned other products in the past and while I am not the Schwarzenegger type for sure, I have managed to break through cheap resistance bands causing pain and/or cuts in various areas of my body. Usually the metal rings would give in under tension and the whole band snapped unexpectedly. That's why at first I was a little hesitant to but this brand and was thinking to settle on more expensive product to assure build quality. I was even more worried after closer examination of the pictures, where I've noticed that what keeps the tube connected is nothing less than the infamous metal ring that likes to fail. However the reviews were good and people mentioned that the customer support is good, so I took the plunge.When I received the product, it wasn't packed in any extravagant box or anything like that, so I wasn't sure my OEM tubes would be good after all. But, after inspecting all elements I've realized that the quality seems good overall. The metal elements appeared to be sturdy and of good quality (I would say B+ quality); the tubes looked good and smooth without any defects, and they streached evenly too; and the handles were OK.So far everything seems to be working fine and I'm slowly regaining trust in resistance bands workouts again, just rarely worrying if something will snap again and hit me.... Maybe this time a piece of the doorframe.What I like about these particular bands is that you can stack them in various combinations to create different tension. So as long as your doorframe is sturdy and you look up few exercise ideas on YouTube and other places you can pretty much work out most of your muscle groups with various exercises. It's also less straining on your joints and creates more resistance throughout the whole movement unlike working out with dumbbells.If you never worked out with the bands, then you should know they are big advantage over dumbbells. I think they work better, are more fun to work out with, are easier to store and are defiantly lighter and more portable. Enjoy!
summary: Quality product for the price of cheap one

I love moleskine products, so I may be slightly biased, but...I used my Kindle for reading academic papers (PDF) and pleasure books. This cover seemed to offer the perfect option, as I need to take notes while I read.It is true, the pocket for the notepad is poorly designed, and the notepad will flop over. It is also true that the design is for a lefty, which is really silly and inconvenient... BUT:I took an exacto knife and cut a slit through the bottom of the pocket, just above the stiching, just slightly longer than the width of the notepad. I then lined the edges of the cut with a tiny bit of masking tape (just to keep it from ripping). I then flipped the DX over, and voila, a righty notepad, and the notepad doesn't flop over.Should I have to do this? No. However, I found it worth the price for a very classy feeling, functional product that will protect my Kindle without damaging it (as some of the Amazon products are purported to do).Cheers.

I have mixed feelings about RS. These reviews should be about the learning aspect of RS, not technical difficulties. I have had a couple of minor glitches, but RS customer service was responsive.I understand the methodology. In a nutshell, I feel that even minimal information on verb tenses or sentence structure or article usage would be incredibly helpful. Fortunately, my Austrian friends are there to help me (although they seem to think I'm silly to try to learn German when they are happy to speak English to me when I visit!). One friend sent me to this [...] to help me understand. It was very early on in Level 1 that I was confused by all the endings added on without explanation. Yes, you may pick up the patterns at some point, but a bit of explanation would be easier.That said, there is so much repetition, you need not fear the next lesson. And it is pretty enjoyable on the whole. I grew up hearing a little bit of German/Yiddish, so the pronunciation has been easy for me. I am a bit fanatical about accents, so I want to get it right. I am bugged that occasionally the voices will differ during the lesson. Ex.: the pronunciation lessons for 'und' and 'fahrrad' make clear that you hit the D pretty much like a T; but when the female voice says 'fahrrad,' she says it like a D.  Same with 'und'--the male voice says it as a D in one phrase.It's hard to imagine becoming anywhere near fluent without the rules and such, but I'm reviewing Level 1, so that's not for me to say.The headset is very nice and solid. So why does each new level come with one?? What a waste! Offer the option of buying the software and using the headset we have.

Castle Ravenloft is an AMAZING introduction to the Dungeons and Dragons Board Game System. It is fun, fast paced and always exciting. It can have 1-5 players and has a high replay value. The miniatures are not painted, but that doesn't really bother me all that much. They are good, solid quality pieces and the tiles are great stock pieces. If there was one thing I would improve on with this set, it is that the miniatures, while good pieces, could be a bit sturdier. They are normal miniature stock, but for my own personal taste, I prefer the pieces to be a bit more rigid (like in the 1990 MB game Heroquest). That is the only real complaint I have. I ordered the Wrath of Ashardalon and the two Dungeon Commander sets to go along with this game. As an avid RPG player, having the miniatures and the tiles is great, and on game days when we can't think of where to go next, the adventures in the book that comes with the sets can be a great jumping off point to segue into the game session.Overall, I give this game 5 stars and congratulate WotC for putting out a fantastic game. High quality, great content and very high replay value.

Disclaimer: This is my first set of exercise bands, so do not consider me an expert on all things resistance bands. WIth that said, I am very happy with my purchase thus far. I purchased these bands a little over 3 months ago and have been using them with the P90x exercise videos among other workouts. The bands feel sturdy and well-made. I admit the first few weeks using the door anchor I half feared the bands would break anyway and snap back to slap me in the face (paranoia anyone?), but they held up beautifully. I find myself putting more and more stress on them now (getting further back from the anchor creates stronger resistance) because I know they can take it. I love the option to stack bands on the handles - there are several leg exercises I do that simply require more weight than a single band in this set can give me. Thankfully, the stacking option works great - the bands feel balanced and like I'm getting even resistance from all of them. I would like it if it were easier to attach and detach the bands from the door anchor, but at the end of the day, I'd rather have an anchor that I know will hold up.There are certain exercises that free weights really are better for, but for the most part, I've done great with these bands and just some 5 lb hand weights as a backup. It is also really easy to switch between bands during a workout, which I appreciate since my workout routines tend to move through several muscle areas and then repeat, and it involves a lot of weight switching. All in all, I recommend!

I'm willing to bet this is STP's overall best album. Here they expand their sound ("Pretty Penny" is mostly acoustic; "Lounge Fly" is, in order, 1/3 Guns n' Roses, 1/3 Crosby, Stills & Nash, and another third Guns n' Roses; "Interstate Love Song" is southern rock) sharpen their songwriting, and come up with something pretty damn good. Okay, so not "Silvergun Superman" or "Meat Plow", flat reworkings of the Core sound. Neither have much personality. I don't really like the slash-and-burn punk song "Unglued" either. It just sounds out of place. But man, "Interstate Love Song" makes up for all of that. The riffs, the vocals, the chorus and the opening are all absolutely perfect. Actually, the entire song is absolutely perfect. I don't think Soundgarden ever made a song as good as that. Or The White Stripes, while I'm at it. "Big Empty" does, too. It goes from slide-driven delta blues to hard-rock in the verses and choruses. You not only get a dynamic shift (which everyone was doing back then), but a stylistic shift, too! And "Army Ants" is a psychedelic hard southern rocker. They even go for a winding, four-minute epic (with hidden track attached, of course) on "Candybars and Kitchenware". A lot of bands would screw this up, but STP gets it perfectly! It's not as good as "Where the River Goes" from the last album, but I don't care, because it's a good song. The lounge-jazz hidden track, an ironic crooned "thank-you-for-listening", is pretty funny, too. I'd hesitate to call anything by the Pilots brilliant, but I enjoy this.
summary: One of the decade's best. No, I'm actually serious. Stop laughing

I got my nook first and thought it was pretty neat until my wife brought home the new kindle. If you put them side by side, you notice that the kindle is a fraction of the thickness, turns pages faster, is easier to navigate (mediocre touch screen on the nook), has several times the battery life, and has much better contrast than the nook. The nook does have a slight advantage in terms of "extras" with a mediocre internet browsing feature and some small applications like sukdo or chess. However, and this was the real killer for me, the kindle can display word documents natively while the kindle can not. Also, the prices seem to be slightly better on amazon for most of the books I have looked at (Sci-Fi) and amazon's website is much easier to navigate then B&N;'s.The biggest problem though with the nook is barnes and noble. They shipped me a unit with a defective battery and agreed to replace it but never sent it. Three months later, 6 promises to send a battery, a complaint filed with the BBB, and there is still no record of them ever having shipped the battery on their computers aside from the one they sent "somewhere in colorado" but can't find any record of what address that might be too. Of course, they stock the batteries in every physical store but you could never simply walk in and pick up the replacement no matter how incompetent their phone support is. From all of my interactions and my friend's experiences with B&N;, this is a common experience with them and undermines whatever they manage to accomplish in terms of producing a decent product.Bottom line: The nook beat the 2nd kindle, but is terrible compared to the 3rd generation of kindle.*note: All software was up to date as of March 2011 on the nook, but still performed worse than the kindle
summary: Good until compared to a kindle

I bought this ice cream maker on Amazon close to two years ago and it is still going strong and making great ice cream! I use it at least twice a week and the ice cream comes out perfect every time. When first made, the ice cream is about the consistency of soft serve or a Wendy's Frosty. That's just fine with me, the flavor is best this way. After freezing whatever is left of the batch, the consistency is like store bought ice cream. I do not do anything fancy with it, just follow the directions in the included booklet for basic vanilla ice cream. In fact, the recipe calls for heavy cream and whole milk but I substitute 1 cup Half & Half and 2 cups low fat (2%) milk to keep it lower cal, and the consistency is still plenty smooth!Like other reviewers have said, be sure to freeze that container for plenty of time before using. Otherwise the ice cream will be real runny. I try to freeze it for 24 hours before use. As long as the directions are followed on this machine, it makes great ice cream every time. Highly recommend it. This is by far my most used kitchen gadget. Love it! Am going to buy another one as a gift right now.
summary: Excellent and easy ice cream machine!

If you are looking at this product, be very careful.  This Amazon item is one of the top search results when looking for an MHL adapter for a Samsung Galaxy S4.  The item heading says it is for the Galaxy S4/SIV, and nowhere in the heading does it mention the S3/SIII.  Yet, when I received this item the box was clearly marked that this MHL adapter is for the S3.  If you read the other reviews, you will find that this has happened to everyone else as well.  The item description also states that this adapter will work on the S4 and s3.  It may work on the S3, who knows, but it does NOT work on the S4 as stated!  I have tried to use this MHL adapter on  multiple televisions using different HDMI cables/ports, and I have tried using my Samsung GS4 retail charger, a Samsung OEM S4 travel charger, and generic chargers.  No configuration has been able to get this item to work on the S4.  Every time my GS4 gives a message that it is "unable to mirror due to hardware failure."  I have a different MHL adapter that works just fine.  So I know the problem is not with any other components.  It appears that everyone posting reviews has had the same problems and has been unable to get this item to work on the S4.  This item simply does not work.  You have been warned.  If you ignore these reviews and buy this item, then do not complain when it does not work and you have to return it.Buy your MHL adapter elsewhere.*** UPDATE ***I purchased my item from the seller "ConneVity." I asked for authorization to return the item and get a refund.  (Most sellers would just approve the authorization, I would ship the item, and they would refund my money.  Not so easy in this case.) ConneVity, to their credit, was very prompt in their responses and their communications were very polite.  However, they were not very helpful.  I feel like I was getting the run-around.  When I asked for a refund they offered an exchange.  They tried to explain to me that the old S3 MHL adapters are the same as the new S4 MHL 2.0 adapters, just that the packaging is different.  When I pointed out how incorrect that was, ConneVity responded with reasons why the old S3 MHL adapter was useful.  Such as how the old S3 adapter can be used on the new S4 and the older S3.  I pointed out that I still wanted a refund because I don't have an S3 and it does NOT work with my S4.  Initially, ConneVity also tried to tell me that nothing was wrong with the item and it was the settings in my S4 that had to be changed.  Twice they said the S4 is not set up to mirror using MHL by default.  I pointed out how that was not true.  My other MHL adapter mirrors with no setting changes, just plug-and-play.  All the video and written tutorials online also demonstrate how the S4 mirrors using MHL by just plugging in the adapter.  I even linked to a written tech tutorial.  Finally, ConneVity admitted that it sounded like the MHL adapter I got was bad.  Now this is when things went from bothersome to truly aggravating.  ConneVity sent me an email containing the following procedure for obtaining a refund."Requires 100% feedback so I can prove to Amazon it works andthey let me force full refunds for future customers.  Then, I email aprepaid label, you return it, email when sent in the mail and I'll issuea full 100% refund, no Amazon penalty, refund issued within 2 businessdays of return shipping confirmation."They require that I give them 100% (positive?) feedback in order to get a full refund on an item that does not work.  They say that I need to prove to Amazon that the item works in order to get a refund when I am returning the item BECAUSE it does not work.  (And no one who left a review has been able to get this item to work on the S4.)  They seem to imply that otherwise I will be penalized by Amazon.  Is that a threat?  You read the message and decide for yourself.  Either way, I do not trust this seller so I went directly to Amazon to verify the truth of the procedure given to me.  I just wanted to know if any of this was actually true.  The Amazon representative who responded was kind enough to file one of Amazon's "A-Z Guarantee" claims for me and is contacting the seller directly!  Amazon also filed a claim with their Seller investigation team because ConneVity's return policy violates Amazon's community rules.At one point, ConneVity was even signing their emails as "Amazon.com for ConneVity" to make it look like I was actually dealing with Amazon employees.  Amazon representatives assured me the person I was talking with was the seller.  Just constant tricks and dishonesty.Just trying to save everyone else a headache.***UPDATE***Again, seller was ConneVity.  Amazon issued a full refund in the form of a gift card, told me to throw out the adapter, stop all communication with the seller, and let Amazon handle it.  (Amazon can always be trusted to do the right thing for customers.  Thank you Amazon.)  Yet seller still contacted me and tried to trick/scare me into editing and removing my feedback.  I contacted Amazon, and Amazon representatives informed me that pretty much everything the seller told me was false.  Sara, ConneVity's owner, emailed me that ConneVity (and I paraphrase) "deserves better feedback under Amazon's feedback agreement and Amazon expects me to remove or edit my feedback."  Amazon confirmed there is no such thing as a "feedback agreement" and I do not have to remove or edit anything.  In fact, the Amazon representative filed another claim with Amazon's seller investigation team because ConneVity's communications violated Amazon's community rules.ConneVity spent 3 paragraphs trying to make me feel guilty and trick me into removing my negative (but deserved) feedback.  Long-story-short, Amazon assured me nothing ConneVity said was true.  Amazon said the communication was cause for investigation and could be cause for ConneVity's removal from Amazon.  Most importantly, be very careful when dealing with this seller.  I advise just shopping elsewhere.
summary: BUYER BEWARE - POSTING IS A LIE!

reviewText: I purchased this in kind of a throwaway moment..."hey, a cheap ice cream maker, what the heck." I wish I had more of those moments! This is a great gadget. When I used it for the first time, I made exquisite Heath Bar Crunch in about 30 minutes. It tastes much better than store-bought ice cream.I highly suggest buying the "factory reconditioned" model from Amazon.com. Same warranty, same product, half the price. Even if you have to wait 4 weeks, it is worth the savings! Mine is perfect.The maker itself looks very nice. After freezing the bowl, you simply pour in your ice cream base (generally milk, cream, eggs and vanilla) and turn it on. It is loud, but it IS an ice cream maker...besides, for 15 minutes, can we not just deal? About 5 minutes before finishing, you add your goodies--chocolate chips, candy pieces, etc. I recommend freezing your creation another 1-2 hours afterward because the consistency can be somewhat like ice milk right away. The ice cream is even better 2-3 days letter if left frozen and covered.Ice cream recipe books are a good compliment, but plenty of recipes are also available online at various places. Overall, I give this my highest recommendation. For the price, you can't beat it. The finished product is excellent and easily created. Cheers!
summary: Ready and easy right out of the box!

reviewText: The lids fit tighter than a teenege girl's jeans, but they do fit! It does take some patience, thumbs, and determination to get them on the first few times but that's why they don't leak. My husband took them out of the box and swore up and down that these were the wrong lids, but I showed him! You have to start at one side and get it locked on and then glide your thumbs around the top outside edge of the cup, one thumb going around counter clockwise and the other going clockwise until they meet on the other side. I've had these cups for years for my three kids' smoothies, juice, milk, yogurt or whatever and no matter how many times they end up toppled over in the fridge, car, or diaper bag they do not leak. Also, it definately takes an adult to open them, so if you are looking to keep your kids out of a container this is the one!

reviewText: I had never made ice cream before.  I had images of ice and rock salt in my head (I wasn't very excited about it).  I knew there had to be a better way to make ice cream.  My sister had given me a book with homemade ice cream recipes in it last year.  My husband and children love ice cream, so I decided to go for it.  Sure enough Cuisinart had a "better" ice cream machine.  The Cuisinart ICE-20 is SO easy to use!  The ice cream recipes vary from simple (combine ingredients and chill) to slightly more advanced (heat some ingredients to make a custard, then chill).  It's SO much fun watching the ingredients go from liquid to solid, and tasting it along the way.  The machine itself has only 4 pieces (no ice or rock salt), and is EASY to assemble.  It's also quiet enough that my children (ages 7 and 5) sleep through it on hot summer evenings when I decide to make a batch to surprise them with in the morning.  So far I've made Vanilla, Strawberry and Cookies and Cream.  I keep the bowl in the freezer so I can whip up a batch whenever I want.  The homemade ice cream disappears so quickly that I just keep making more and more.  I'm looking forward to the next flavor to try - coffee, mint chocolate chip, lemon sherbet - so many to choose from.  This machine also makes sorbets, frozen yogurt and frozen drinks - Mmmm!  I'm addicted!

Fun activity for school aged kids.My kids enjoyed doing their own illustrations and seeing them in print.For the extra fee, it's worth getting the "archival" finish for the pages.Otherwise you just end up with the original paper that your kid drew on, bound in a hardcover book, which doesn't have the same cachet as the more professional finished look & smooth feel.I was a little bummed about that the first time we did it, not realizing that by cheaping out on the extra fee I was just getting the same paper, bound in hardcover.I loved the "about the author" feature because it is just so cute having a little bio and photo at the end!  A simple wallet-sized school photo does the trick, so you don't have to feel bad about sending off a more expensive passport photo, or whatever.It's also cute having the author dedication at the beginning.
summary: pay the extra for the additional archival page finish

reviewText: We received this coffee maker as a gift this Christmas. Very nice thought, but it's the worst coffee maker that we have ever owned.#1)Multiple parts must be cleaned well before each brew - not only the grinds in the basket, but the grinds in the grinder as well as two additional lid pieces. Pain!#2)The beans and grinds get wet with the steam from the hot water, so much so that 1/4 of the grinds remain in the grinder.#3)The grinder leaves whole beans unground, again due to the steam.#4)It's loud, even louder than our burr grinder.#5)It just broke! The little arm that the lid clicks onto to open and close broke. SO, in order to make anything, I have to have something heavy sitting on top of it to click close. Otherwise, it just keeps beeping.Why don't I just toss it? I would, but my son and his girlfriend bought it for us, probably spent a lot of $ that they don't have on it and they come over often enough that I just can't. :(

First, let me start with the summary. Do not buy a Nook Tablet. I own one and I wish I didn't. On paper, I consider it the best 7" tablet for the price. A wonderful display, quick and responsive, micro SD slot...up to 32 gig and 16 gig on board with an Android OS and only $250! Now, the reality, at least according to me. I was very happy with the screen quality and the responsiveness of the unit. 16gig of on board memory...ha! 15gig of that memory is reserved for ONLY material purchased from Barnes and Nobel. You only have 1 gig to install your own media. That's about 200 mp3s or about 45min of mp4 video. That's right! Even though you bought 16gig of data space, Barnes and Nobel is holding 15gig of it for ransom! Now for the micro SD slot. The Nook manual says it supports class 6. I tried a 16gig class 10 and a 32gig class 4 card and had video playback problems with both cards (less with the class 4). I also had some mp3 playback problems with the class 4 card. The Nook had occasional problems even identifying the class 4 card. I have yet to track down a class 6 card at a local vendor. I have no conclusion on this matter, though there are possibilities. There is no flexibility, a class 6 card is the only option (good luck finding a 32gig class 6 card...I am aware that a class 10 card should be compatible, just function as a class 6 card...that's just the tech side of me talking, I know it doesn't always work that way). It is also possible that the micro SD slot is just crappy and there'll be problems with any card. As for the Android OS...not really. This ia a Barnes and Nobel custom version of Android. That means that ONLY apps found on the Barnes and Nobel site are available. The Nook will block apps from any other source. All preloaded apps cannot be deleted. Look over the apps on the Barnes and Nobel site to see if you're satisfied with the choices, I wasn't. That's about it.

Does this do everything it's advertised to do?  Well, I can't prove to  you if my left and right brains are communicating better, but I can tell you that the ball of whacks gives you an often much needed literal and figurative "timeout" so you can contemplate the big picture and the little details.  From a sensory perspective, it's fun to manipulate the pieces and I like to leave myself signals (sharp points or rounded symmetry) of my mood on the table.  Shapes change as do my moods; a good tool for developing EQ.  The use of magnets/magnetism as part of the problem solving or creative exercise comes close to the "stacrobats"  concept, but instead of soft figures and balls, you have all these wonderful points and pieces that reward the auditory and tactile sense with a satisfying "snick".  Enjoy - have a ball!

I am a 45 year old mom of three:  13yrs/10yrs/2yrs.  College educated education major, now I am a stay-at-home mom.  With one income coming in; I search high and low for a bargain.  I shop yardsales, and thrift stores to get gently used items rather than ever pay retail.  However, I NEVER have a problem putting Illustory on the 'pay full price and get this thing' list.We always get these for our kids because it is a wonderful way to share time with them as you create a story together(my daughter like to have me illustrate a story she writes - and trust me I am no Picasso). It is also a wonderful way for your kids to express who they are by...get this...actually writing and drawing.  NO ELECTRONIC GADGET is ever going to give your child the satisfaction they get when their very own creation comes back in a beautiful printed book.Can you make your own book at home?  Sure, but it's not the same and I can't make a hardcover book, can you?In my humble opinion, this is a home run gift for any ocassion.  I also suggest more board games as gifts.  You can't beat spending time with your kids as an antidote to all the garbage competing for their attention in the world.By the way, why not have your kids use this 'book' to write and draw about a family member and give the published book to that person.  For ex:  a book about the things they love to do with Gram/Gramps or an uncle, or even an teacher!  There are so many ways this product could be used!  Yes, definitely check out the Illustory web site.
summary: Skip the Electronics - BUY THIS ITEM!

reviewText: I asked my husband to buy this machine for me for Christmas instead of jewelry, and have no regrets!  I love all the sorbets, ice milks and ice creams that we can make.  It is simple to use, and the results taste great!My only complaint is how loud the machine is.  I can't really let the machine run while we are having dinner unless I put the ice cream maker far away from the kitchen and dining room.  But other than that inconvenience, I can't complain.I would agree with the other reviewers -- use cold ingredients, and start your ice cream as soon as you take the bowl out of the freezer.  I let my bowl freeze for at least two days before using it.  I put it in a plastic bag, and then put a zip-loc bag of ice in the container just to be sure.I have a hard time using all of the egg yolks and heavy cream to make true "ice cream" (although a splurge once in awhile isn't a bad thing!).  I try to stick to the lower fat recipes.  You can find endless recipes and ideas on the internet.  I must admit that when in a hurry I just throw together some milk, half and half, real mexican vanilla, sugar, and a pinch of salt (no recipe here, just taste it to your own creaminess and sweetness level) to make ice cream for dessert.  It's like having fresh soft serve.  Yum!If you would like your own ice cream maker, you can't go wrong with this machine!
summary: Easy to use and makes GREAT product!

Who needs a case that must be removed every time you want to take a flash shot. And its not easy to remove at that. I inherited one of these that was my grandma's and I am already thinking of buying a second bowl since I have been making ice cream so frequently. This is just as easy as running to the store and buying a carton of additive-packed ice cream. Freeze the bowl, mix your ingredients, fire it up, add your mixture, blend-blend-blend, ice cream. The owner's manual comes with many recipes and with sites like Pinterest I have discovered many more. One of my favorites is 1 cup frozen pink lemonade concentrate, 3 cups milk, and 3 tbsp Splenda for a tangy frozen treat. I use fat free milk, so I tend to get 'icier' blends than using full fat milk for creamier results, but softening at room temp for a minute or two makes it very easy to scoop and a batch lasts about a week (mostly because it is my daily treat). A tip: do not use a metal sppon to scrape the bowl, it will leave unsightly scratch marks. Hopefully I did not ruin my bowl by doing that.

I have been interested and wanted to know more about D&D; for well over 20yrs, but I always seemed so busy and to take on a new "hobie" and find the time for it was next to impossible. Well now I am disabled and have a lot of time on my hands for checking out all the things I did not have time for when I was younger. I seen this game on Amazon and although it's from 2006 I just had to have it for the price, (under $[...]). I did a little research on The web site "Wizards of the Coast" [...] I have also been learning the Trading Card Game "Magic the Gathering" which you will find on the same site. I learned that the world of D&D; seemed to have more than one variation of D&D; games, and this game was geared to teach you the basics of "D&D; Miniatures" and comes with everything to get you and some friends a good base to start at. You get a 12 miniature figures of Heroes, Monsters and a cool Blue Dragon. 4 booklets for each Hero and a basic Dungeon Master booklet, dice, dungeon tiles, 1 sheet of counters - doors, chests etc. made of glossy cardboard, a getting started 1pg sheet and an Advanced Rule book. This being my 1st D&D; game I think it has everything to get you started and if you like it you will have a good foundation to move on to other versions of the game. I also bought this game:Dungeons & Dragons Roleplaying Game Starter Set (D&D; Introductory Game), which is similar except it starts on the new version D&D; 4 and has cardboard discs instead of the minitures. I have been reading through each set and I think for the price I got much more than I expected, and look forward to get on with playing them. I think I picked a great starting point for the game and recommend anyone interested in D&D; to get this set! As a newbie I give it 5 stars!

reviewText: This was my first time buying a "deck builder's toolkit," but I do have a small MTG card collection and have played casually for many years.  For the price, this is a good way to start out or have a fun match-n-grab evening with some friends.  For card value directly, you can do better for the cost.  104 of the cards are basic land, and none of the non-booster cards are rares.  All of the non-booster cards, 125 of the remaining 181 cards, are either commons (mostly in groups of two, some four) or uncommon (one-ups or pairs).  The boosters each contain 14 cards, plus a basic land (counted in the 104 land total above), plus a token or tip card.  Of those, each booster contains one rare (making a grand total of four rare cards within the 285 in the kit).The box is good-quality cardboard with nice graphics, and will likely prove to be fairly durable.  It holds around 400 sleeved cards (~500 bare).Card Count Recap:Basic Land:  104Common/Uncommon:  177Rare:  4Total Playing Cards:  285"Bonus" Cards (tokens/tips):  4
The box contains most of the famous characters like Artemis Entreri and Catti-brie. This is a must have collection for Dungeon and Dragon, Forgotten Realm, fans.
summary: Wizards of The Coast Legend of Drizzt: A Dungeons and Dragons Board Game

reviewText: Most people my age (I'm 23) aren't interested in great eReaders like the Kindle or Nook Color, they'd rather have the self-proclaimed "best tablet on the market" iPad. Thankfully, I'm not like most people my age.For a brief moment I wanted to get the iPad because of one reason, I wanted to read magazines. Then I realized that a device the could carry all of my books as well as my stacks of magazines would be a ideal for me. That's where the Kindle and Nook Color came in...Some people think it's a matter of either or when it comes to these two products, but I think we need both on the market. So this is what it comes down to:If you are a serious, die-hard ereader who wants to read for hours on-end without getting tired or outdoors without glare, then the Kindle is the best choice for you. It's eInk looks so incredible you will find it hard to believe it's a tablet and not a real page. And if that wasn't enough the battery can last up to a month!I came VERY close to getting this great product, but then I tried the Nook Color...The Nook Color can only be described in one word, PERFECTION! Some people don't like the weight of it but I actually do, it might be heavier than the Kindle but it's more durable and better to hold this way. To be honest, the Kindle was so lightweight that at times it feels like it will snap in half. The Nook Color's screen is unbelievably beautiful, it's clear, crisp, and simply stunning. Book covers look amazing sitting on the shelf in your library and magazines will blow you away. This is why it beats the iPad on every level; its better for reading ebooks, better for reading magazines, and it's much more portable. As a student my messenger bag is already heavy enough because of all my textbooks, the last thing I need is a bulky, 9 inch, heavy tablet like the iPad. Not too mention it's insane price tag, I can barely afford textbooks so throwing $500 at Steve Jobs is not an option. That's why I decided I'd rather have an ereader under my tree this year instead of an over-sized, glorified iPod Touch (especially when I already have an iPod Touch.) But ereaders like the Nook Color and Kindle are perfect for people like me.The Nook store has every book the Kindle store does, (so far from what I've seen), and they get more ebooks and magazines on a regular basis. And the interactive children's books are great for reading stories to my nephews and niece. Plus the Nook Color designer covers are the perfect addition to you Nook, they can be a bit pricey but they are attractive and well-made, a great investment! And for those of you who think it might be hard/tricky to figure out just hang in there, the set-up vids that play straight away are really helpful and will explain whatever the instruction booklet might have left out.So if you want to read books, look at magazines, listen to your music, read interactive children's books, view your photo albums all in a tablet that's actually the weight and size of a real book then buy the Nook Color! So might have to sacrifice the eink and the long battery life, but trust me it's well worth it, you won't regret getting the Nook Color.

reviewText: This set is a very fine game that can be played in less than an hour or more. The miniatures in the set alone make it an impressive edition to any D&D player. Aside from the 42 miniatures, there is several sheets of interlocking card stock tiles representing the areas you explore. I purchased this game after reading and watching several reviews online. Neither my wife nor I has ever played a table-top RPG game, though I am somewhat familiar with the world of D&D; from a handful of the novels that I've read, the toys I had as a kid and the 80s cartoon. That was about the extent of my D&D; experience and my wife didn't even have that much.To make it short, we love the game! We played it nearly every night for about a month and our lack of experience with D&D; gaming was not an issue at all. We loved it so much I bought the sequel game Wrath of Ashardalon and we started playing it last night.It's a brutal game and we lose a lot, but that's what makes the victories worthwhile. The rulebook is kept fairly simple, which is good for the casual gamer. It might frustrate people who want to have every possibility covered in the rulebook, but we found that this lack of specificity encourages people to come up with their own "House Rules" that cover some of those special circumstances that aren't covered in the rules. We enjoy the creativity that this allows the players to use while playing. In addition, the game is different every time you play it, making the replayability a huge plus. It also allows you to create your own adventures/scenarios.On a final note, all the game pieces, cards, etc are excellent. They are very sturdy and durable, much more so than the average board game.If you like cooperative games in a fantasy setting, give this game a chance.
summary: Lots of fun and don't have to be an RPG gamer

reviewText: I just got this mini processor yesterday and I absolutely love it!  I couldn't be happier with it so far.First, the size is just excellent for small jobs and for easy storage -- tucked away on the countertop or in a cabinet.Second, it works beautifully -- I've already made two of the recipes in the enclosed booklet -- homemade mayonnaise and tuna salad.  Both are simply delicious and it's great to work with small amounts.Several reviewers have expressed dissatisfaction with this -- citing it's tendency to break after a few tries or produce inconsistent results.  I haven't had any of these problems.  The instruction manual is extremely clear about two things -- the food must be chopped into small pieces before adding to the processor, and, you can't run the motor continuously for longer than 1 minute.  However, that is no problem -- I made thick, fluffy mayonnaise and nearly accidentally pureed some celery and onion by just pulsing with the blunt blade.  So, while small, it's very powerful when used correctly.This is an excellent kitchen item and perfect for anyone needing to save space and prepare small amounts of food.

My brother is a trucker and pre-ordered this.  He was out on the road when it arrived, so he asked me to charge it, update it, and play with it.  FUN!  I am not a trucker, but from what I hear from my brother, the tools on this device are awesome.  It looks like it would be very helpful for him.  The thing is huge, a 7" screen!  Overall, this seems to be a great tool.My problem with it is that it cannot update.  I have a brand new computer running Windows 7 64 bit.  It's a Dell Studio XPS 8100 (i5 processor).  After reading on forums and contacting Rand McNally, I have learned that Windows 7 does not send enough power to the USB ports to allow the TND 700 to go into "connected" mode when it's plugged in to a computer.  Supposedly this is a problem that occurs mostly with laptops and some Dell systems ("Dell Latitude or Inspiron PC (it may occur on other models as well)").  Rand McNally send a very helpful email with some solutions to the problem, though it sounds like they are still unsure of all fixes or what causes the problem.  I am disappointed that a brand new device does not work with a brand new operating system, though that seems to be the nature of all things now-a-days.  I am hoping that it will update on my brother's XP laptop. we'll see when he gets back home.

Pesto, bread crumbs (including a batch of WAY overbaked croutons that were rock hard), spices, coffee beans, graham cracker crust (for a very tiny pie)... it's pleased me every time.My two favorite things: it comes with a little mini spatula, which allows you to get nearly every drop of whatever you're prepping out of the processor and into your recipe, which isn't always the case w/food processors - big or small. reviewText: I got this for the 2nd Birthday of the most precious girl that I watch.  I know that she is going to love it....I do.  Well made and just the right size.  The "stuff" inside is fun.  She loves to carry her things around in something and this fits all the bases.

This "miniature" is one of the biggest ever that is still to scale with the standard D&D; sized minis. The construction is well-done, as is the paintjob, and it depicts a truly massive red dragon quasi-rearing up as if to strike downward or to breathe a gout of flame (more on that in a moment).I've already had the chance to pull this big boy out and use it in game (a PC shapechanged into a colossal red dragon), and it is quite impressive when actually placed on a battle mat and set against other figures. The weirdest thing is that it makes the gargantuan black dragon, which, when I first got it, seemed immense, now look positively puny!Those are the good points of the mini. But there are two bad points. The first is important IMO. For reasons I cannot quite understand, they made the mini the wrong size. Yep. A colossal red dragon is supposed to be 30 ft square. This one is 40 ft square. Now, as some have pointed out, the definition of colossal in the Monster Manual says colossal creatures are AT LEAST 30 ft square, but can be bigger. But the red dragon entry in the Monster Manual only lists 30 ft square as the proper size of a colossal red dragon.Can I, as a DM, rationalize an extra 10 ft? Yeah. But it is still an annoying thing...and sometimes even more. As a DM I might have designed a cavern or dungeon to fit a colossal red dragon and made the halls 30 ft wide. Oops! Now my red dragon mini doesn't even fit in my dungeon! It also distorts the reach of the dragon. A 30 ft square dragon with reach threatens many fewer squares than a 40 ft square dragon with reach. This can make a large difference in combat.But really, the increase simply seems unecessary. Why did WOTC make it bigger than the proper size? What compelling reason was there to do this? None that I can think of.Devin

Granted, this film diverts from Mark Twain's classic novel more often than it should.However, this is a musical.... and I hope will be judged as such.I was disappointed in the fact that the original story is quite diluted.... even to the point of having only two boys (Tom and Huck) run away to Jackson's Island, with no Joe Harper in sight.Yet I still enjoyed this film.  The songs were fun and original, and admittedly, I'm a bit partial to musical productions anyway.Johnny Whitaker plays a believable "Tom", and Jeff East is well cast as the rugged "Huck".  With a very young Jody Foster in the role of Tom's "Becky", the casting was above par.And although many aspects & elements of Twain's classic novel are missing from this rendition..... Tom is still that barefooted, mop-headed youngster - - full of mischief and quick to gain sympathy from even the most hard-hearted of souls... and this is the true character of a young Tom Sawyer.... whom even Samuel Clemens could not deny as an epitome of the semi-autobiographical boyhood novel he chose to create.
summary: As a musical version - - - four stars

reviewText: This is THE BEST fool proof way of making ice cream.  No more messing with salt and ice cubes--this maker has a special bowl that you keep in the freezer that freezes the ingredients (mine is always frozen so whenever I want to make ice cream I can). This machine comes with a pretty thorough booklet with ice cream recipes in it but you can make "frozen ANYTHING" with this maker.  Did you know that you could make frozen pudding? The ice cream technique that Cuisinart has perfected of a constant scraping of the sides of the bowl assures that your ice cream is super smooth too. Make as little or as much as over a quart at a time.  Great machine!  I've had mine for about six years and use it about once a month and it is still as quiet as the day I bought it.
summary: Ice cream in a snap--buy no other!

reviewText: Have you ever thought about how you met your best friend? Was it normal, or was it wacky - like how Elias met Shohei? Pulling a boa constrictor snake named Mathilda out of your backpack can make a remarkable first impression! This book is about three best friends Elias, Honoria, and Shohei, who are united against "That Which Is The Peshtigo School". Their goal is to make it through the annual school science fair, but things don't always go as planned.Elias is part of a family made up of science fanatics who would do anything to win a science fair. Elias isn't exactly what you'd call the ambitious type, especially when it comes to science fairs. So he becomes like Galileo and "retests" one of his sibling's past projects. Honoria loves to be ambitious, especially when it comes to being a legal counsel extraordinaire. But when she faces a bigger challenge than beating Goliath Reed or getting a piranha to become vegetarian, she doesn't know if she can make it. Shohei is an all around slacker who tries to mooch off Elias instead of creating something on his own. His adoptive parents are constantly encouraging him to start "hearing" his ancestors. His mom has even turned Shohei's room into what looks like a walk-in Japanese museum exhibit!This book is laugh out loud hilarious and the more you read, the more exciting and unexpected it gets. I love the title on this book because it really made me laugh and want to read the book. I also like how people so different from one another can be such close friends. There is not much excitement in the beginning, but it builds up very quickly. So if you like that type of story, then this is the book for you.

Coconut milk based ice cream is a close second! :)

reviewText: When I first got this, it had version 1.1.1 on it and there WERE issues.  Especially concerning bookmarks and remembering the last read page. reviewText: This is a simple and quick solution for converting Computer Video and Sound to an old fashioned cathode ray tube TV.I own an old Sony Trinitron TV, which was tops in it's day, but completely obsolete in today's world.  Although this TV has been left behind by technology, there is actually nothing wrong with it - the picture and sound are as great as they always were.  It sits in our basement entertainment center, connected to an old DVD player, and an even older VCR.  I mainly used it for exercise videos and to allow my grandchildren to watch movies without disturbing the entire house.However I thought we could get better use from the Old Sony and wanted to use it for streaming Amazon Instant videos.  I didn't know exactly how to accomplish this, so I took it to my local office store and asked one of their computer tech guys to recommend something to convert PC to CRT, making it possible to view computer tv programs and movies on the old Sony Trinitron.  They didn't have the correct set up in the store, so we went online right at the service desk and searched Amazon for a solution.After reviewing several possibilities, we decided that this gadget would do the trick, and I ordered it online there and then.  I didn't know if it would really work, but at this price it was worth a try.  It arrived within a week, and was simple, straightforward and effective!  Everything was included, and it was all very easy to do.  The instructions were brief - they didn't need to be longwinded because the set up is so seamless and idiot - proof.  First, I found an unused input on the TV and plugged in the red/white/yellow plugs on the converter.  Then I attached the appropriate connections to my laptop and turned everything on.  Voila!  The TV became and instant computer monitor and speaker for my computer.  I proceeded to play a movie on Amazon instant video and everything worked like a charm.Now when anyone in the house wants to watch a computer movie on a big TV screen, all they have to do is connect to this great and inexpensive converter!  The flat screen TV we have in the family room will do this without a converter, but who wants the whole house filled with the noise of movies and TV programs playing all the time.  It is nice to have a place that is not so central where people can watch programs without disturbing everyone in the house.  And I like having access to the exercise videos that are available online.This is everything I like in a computer device - it is simple and reliable.  And it is only a fraction of what I thought I might have to pay.

I decided to write this review while researching other watches.  I was reading watch reviews by people who had their new watch for days and weeks.  I have had my Vector for ten years, so I thought I would share.  I rock climb, surf, and play volleyball.  I never take my watch off.  It's still ticking.  I've replaced the battery a number of times.  Yes, the crystal is scratched and I have torn my band in half a couple times, but the guts of the watch just keep going.  I only rock climb and surf two or three times a year.  But I play volleyball two or three times a week.  I am about the only guy who leaves his watch on during games.  And why not.  This watch can handle anything.  I just bought another comparatively expensive sport watch from another retailer (a green Nison "Unit" watch) just so I can have a watch with color (my Suunto is black). It is a large watch face, as you must already know.  But I am a large guy.  I can't wear something the size of a dime on my wrist. I needed a silver dollar and this is it.

I needed a tablet to make studying for college classes easier than on my laptop.I bought mine at Best Buy and was immediately pleased with the sleek design after opening the box. Easily my favorite looking tablet cosmetically. After booting it up and installing the updates for Google Play and so on I was up and running. The screen resolution and quality was really gorgeous, more pixel resolution than most, a great value considering how cheap this tablet now is! The dual core processor was noticeably a little slow, not nearly a s fluid as the Nexus 7 I now have with it's quad core processor. People who say that quad core is only necessary for gaming are mistaken, it effects everything, such as waiting time between opening and closing apps, returning to the home screen, loading web pages, even how fluid you can navigate from page to page of your apps.At $150-180 this is still a great value even with a slower processor and the exclusion of the Amazon App store (which is home to the majority of my already purchased apps) The real shame it the heating issue.Within a week I returned my first Nook because it kept overheating and force shutting down. I returned it for a new one in hopes that it was a fluke, but two days later had the same overheating issues. The XDA Developer forums seem to agree that many Nook HD + tablets have heating issues due to it's microprocessor in the lower left side of the device...exactly where mine would heat up before shutting itself down.This was obviously a pretty huge design flaw. I tried two different tablets and both were force shutting down just about every other day due to regular use....not playing graphics heavy games. I I were to rate this tablet as dependable or not dependable I'd say it's really not. If the device had sold better in the first place you'd think there would be a recall, but instead they're being clearanced out.Pros- Really sleek design, Gorgeous high resolution screenCons- Overheating/ force shutting down, slower dual core processor. No Amazon App store
summary: Looks great (sleek design, resolution) but severe overheating problems and slow processor.

reviewText: Unfortunately, I'm not actually able to rate the software itself because it never ran on my Windows 8.1 PC - producing the Fatal Application Error #1141.  All available fix options suggested on the Rossetta support site have been tried without success.  Writing support, it was suggested that I remove my antivirus and anti-malware software.  Even if that were to be successful, it would still be an unacceptable `solution' since it would be useless and dangerous to run the PC without them -- just so I could run Rosetta software.  The internet has many, many people making the same complaint -- and many of them are using protection software other than what I'm using (Zone Alarm and MalWarebytes) .  I even tried it on two different PC's.  The second PC runs windows 7.0.  The same result occurred.If it works for you, that's great.  It doesn't for me.

I hate the way everyone seems to get away with outright lying about stated battery capacity, but that being said, a geniune 18650 battery SHOULD produce at least 1800mAh. The top of the line goes to about 3000mAh, but the price jump for such quality is substantial, search for Panasonic 18650's and you'll see what I mean.  These have 1850mAh tested capacity, which is actually pretty good for this price. Your price may vary, see dealer for details....  ;)I went through 14 different vendors/brands and only found FOUR that were 1800mAh or above, the rest were counterfeit. What does counterfeit mean? It means that if you cut it open (don't do that) you will find a bunch of sawdust (or similar filler material) and then you will find a very tiny AAA sized battery stuck inside this huge empty 18650 shell, with leads soldered to the positive and negative terminals. No kidding. My first set of 18650's put out a whopping 160mAh, so I knew something was seriously wrong and I DID cut them open.Unless you want to take your chances elsewhere, I seriously recommend getting these here. They aren't the best but I can verify they are genuine, and no slow boat from China. Half of the 14 sets I went through came from Amazon and went straight back to Amazon. The other half came from China and I'm stuck with the bad ones.
summary: 1850mAh tested capacity, which is actually pretty good for this price.

reviewText: Everyone seems to love Lords of Waterdeep as a lighter worker placement game.  But why?  Lets take a look.COMPONENTSThe board is completely functional.  Your player markers are completely functional.  The cards are OK.  Some of the text on them is a bit small and difficult for people not right next to them to read.  Money is cardboard chits and are a bit weird, but once you get used to which shape/size is what value, it's good enough.  Everything else?  Cubes.  Warriors?  Cubes.  Wizards?  Cubes.GAMEPLAYYou take turns placing your workers which let you take quests or resources to complete those quests and/or draw/play cards, and then if you can/want to, you then spend resources to complete one of your quests.  Completing a quest gives you points and many times, more resources to spend later.  Additionally, you can take an action to "buy" a new action space to be put on the board (which you can take or, if anyone else takes it, you get a kickback for owning it).Additionally, there are some hidden bonuses for completing certain types of quests (each player has different hidden goals).  What it really ends up meaning is, if you're lucky and can get goals which don't have a lot of competition (so others aren't taking your quests) and are lucky enough for your type of quests to show up as being available, you get a few extra points.  It's generally not game-altering.All in all, the gameplay is very solid.  My only problem with the gameplay is the cards.  Far too many of them are very "take that" play against one other player.  So if you're in the lead, get ready to get "blue shelled" quite a bit.  As a lighter game, that's not the worst thing in the world.THEMEThe theme is recruiting a small army to go on quests and do cool things, which will look familiar to those familiar to the D&D; lore.  In reality, the game always seems to come down to people paying attention to nothing but colors of cubes to collect and colors of cubes on the cards.  If the cubes were meeples of what they were representing, it would be much easier to feel the theme.  If the different types of quests actually felt different, that would help as well.  As is, it just feels like collecting resources to complete your shopping list.  The theme is a major letdown.CONCLUSIONIf you look at the reviews on Amazon for this game, you'll see literally nothing below 3 stars.  And you know why that is?  It's impossible to hate this game.  Unfortunately, if you know the better options for this type of game, you'll realize it's not easy to love, either.  The mechanics are mostly sound, but there's nothing that stands out anywhere.  The theme isn't there.  And there's better options for simpler worker placement games (The Manhattan Project, Alien Frontiers) to use to teach newer board gamers.  Do yourself a favor and play one of the better options.
summary: Lords of Waterdeep: A worker placement game with no heart

Among the concerts that I have attended over five decades  four Cherkassky performances hold a special place. His biographies inform us that a young Glenn Gould was mesmerized upon witnessing Josef Hoffmann in concert, and walked around in a kind of trance days afterwards. Well, I shared this experience during Cherkassky's concerts in the 80's, Hofmann, one of his teachers, could have been proud.Unfortunately, Cherkassky's quality of tone, about which libraries could be filled to little avail, is poorly reproduced in most of his recordings. His Nimbus discs are disastrous, his concert discs on Decca, Orpheo and BBS legends are decent, but offer very little in the way of the Cherkassky live experience. Fortunately, there is this disc that should be able to give an uninitiated listener at least some impression of the singing tone that the master could produce on any hall's standard issue.Just like Jorge Bolet, whose late Liszt cycle has endowed him with a distinctly better chair in the pianist pantheon, Cherkassky found his highest acclaim towards the end of a distinguished career. He started out a prodigy, found fame, was forgotten and survived under humble circumstances as the BBC house pianist, to reemerge in the 1980s and find well deserved acclaim.Whereas the likes of Ivo Pogorelich and Bruno Leonardo Gelber never failed to express the attitude "my audience, I despise you"; never more so when one attempted to even approach their dressing room, Shura was the very opposite. He knew who he was and was the most pleasant of after concert personalities. I remember discussing the Beethoven/Liszt symphony transcriptions that Katasaris was recording at that time with him. He responded "o, that is such a bad idea, those works don't work at all on a piano; and, "the Liszt version of Berlioz' Symphonie Fantastique, now that is a much better idea". However, my question "have you ever played it" only got one of his gentle "are you crazy" smiles in response.In his Cherkassky obituary Stephen Hough wrote: "no one who heard him play or met him will ever forget his unique personality, both on and off the stage. His golden tone, like sunshine melting a bowl of the richest ice-cream (two of his 'favourite things'); his contrapuntal voicing, like a child wandering into all the rooms he's been banned from; or, for that matter, his walk to the piano - as if treading on crushed velvet. We will try to keep our memories fresh with his recordings (particularly the 'live' ones), and will treasure amongst ourselves the many anecdotes which have now become part of musical folklore. Although he never taught ("I wouldn't know how"), perhaps we can all learn from him the lesson that elegance and entertainment have their place in the concert hall as well as education and elevation; and that there is no shame in loving and cherishing the piano for its own sake."And, although Cherkassky could wrap his arms around a Liszt sonata, the Tchaikovsky Sonata included on this disc, or other large scale works, his mastery was best attuned to both smaller scale works, or segmentable works like variations and paraphrases.It was in one of the after concert conversations that in response to a tease by what appeared a longtime friend Cherkassky responded "well, look at my repertoire, it ranges from Lully to Stockhausen, and a lot of what is in between". That was interesting, and after spending quite some time in those pre-internet days, I was disappointed to find out that there were no such things as Lully solo keyboard works. Two decades later, this disc came to the rescue.Technically this disc is so, so. It's a live concert with a lot of audience noise. There is tape hiss. Dynamics at the macro level are ok, on the micro level leave a lot to be desired, but timbre wise this disc is not bad at all.The concert starts with Lully. Now, in the internet age, I found out that the "suite de Pieces" that Cherkassky played is in fact the pianist's selections from an early 20th century transcription of Lully Opera pieces for the piano. Those interested should be able to find the score as a free download without trouble.In many interviews Cherkassky has admitted that sitting on a podium in front of an audience took him to a places that he would have never imagined during practice sessions, and that relistening to concert recordings often resulted in a "did I really play it that way?" response. Well, his Lully here is a fine example. Fine that is, for those who do not suffer from HIPP hang ups, since they may counter that Cherkassky's trance-like performance channels good old Beelzebub. But, and this is very relevant for Lully, the French state "c'est le ton qui fait la musique", and it is his pretty much unmatched tone control that enables Cherkassky's to open emotional doors, that don't budge for the great majority of his colleagues. Sure, one could remark that this performance -remember Hough's "his contrapuntal voicing, like a child wandering into all the rooms he's been banned from" - is pathologically anachronistic. But, that gently perfumed "Air tendre" represents the composer more credible than many a card carrying HIPP vinegar factory. To me, this Lully is amazing. And, admiration for this interpretation really blooms when one climbs behind the 88 with the score. Talk about artistic imagination.Mendelssohn's decidedly third-tier piano trifles were popular in Cherkassky's generation. He makes out of it what he can, but this Scherzo and Cappriccio has never impressed me.Next, we get to the meat and potatoes of this disc, the nowadays mostly forgotten Tchaikovsky sonata. It's sad Pjotr wrote so much great music, and yet when it comes to the piano all we hear is that mediocre 1st Piano Concerto war horse. In many respects, this sonata is much more interesting. Of course, a Hammerklavier it's not, but judged on its own especially melodic merits there is a lot to enjoy. The pianist has this music running through his veins and in all likelihood offers us a very close approximation of what Tchaikowsky had in mind. Not surprisingly, the interpretation is approached from the inside out, from detail to the whole -Leslie Howard offers an engagingly opposite approach. And, the romantically inclined among us will find a lot to enjoy in this neglected work.Next, there is Chopin's Op. 61, which may be considered among the composer's very best and most dramatic works. Although I don't want to imply that it represented a certain dislike of the dramatic, Cherkassky's performance here is in a much lighter vein than Ivan Moravec' standard performance. Just like he did in his Salzburg performance of Bach's 6th Partita, Cherkassky provides a more laid back approach that does not lack in validity. Chopin's masterpiece does lose some of its bite, but this lyrical approach successfully highlights the more subtle of the composer's modulations in a beautiful tone.Then there are two encores, an old school Chopin waltz that defines the word "charm" concludes the affair. Before that there is Hoffman's Kaleidoskop, that has been revived by Marc-Andre Hamelin. The Canadian is linear and metronomically incredibly perfect. Just like in Lully, Cherkassky dives into the piece, and uses his exquisite sense of coloring to get to this composition's true essence.Bolet and Cherkassky both enjoyed the label "the last romantic" at the end of their careers. Comparing them to today's highly homogenized lot turns even me nostalgic. Fortunately, this disc seves like the madeleine in "À la recherche du temps perdu".
summary: An adequate representation of a unique pianist

There are plenty of reviews here discussing the techinical aspects of the Nook vs other e-readers so I won't cover those details.  I like the color, the back lit screen, and the online capabilities.  I get no eye strain from the back lighting, I love that aspect.Two stars for customer service.My problem stems from Barnes and Noble's company policy regarding replacement of defective units.  My Nook Color developed problems being able to consistently connect to a wifi signal, at home, remotely, or at a Barnes and Noble store.  I've had my Nook for 7 months now and this problem has gotten worse over time.  I spoke w/ a tech support person once who was no help, then a second who said I needed a replacement.  A few days later I received a replacement, pretty quick, impressed; until I opened the box and found a CERTIFIED PRE-OWNED NOOK.  When I called customer support, they couldn't give me a straight answer about why that happened but with all the nonsensical things they told me, I deduced that it is Barnes and Noble policy to send certified pre-owned replacements to replace a defective unit. After several attempts I finally was able to talk to a manager who confirmed that policy.  If your Nook malfunctions beyond 30 days of purchase, you will receive a used Nook.  Even w/ an extended warranty, which by the way, in the store, I was told I'd get a brand new replacement, apparently the extended warranty only covers you for a certified pre-owned previously defective Nook.The Nook Color is great, as long as it is working properly.  Have one go bad and good luck to you!

I remember having a strange contraption of an ice cream maker when we were young.  I remember that we never succeeded at making ice cream.  The result of a half hour of concocting and endlessly turning the crank was an unfrozen milk mixture that had many large frozen ice crystals in it that was hardly recognizable as ice cream.  It was more like what you get when you accidentally let store bought ice cream thaw completely and then re-freeze it.Naturally, I was a bit skeptical about this when I saw it showcased on Amazon's front page.  After reading many rave reviews and checking out what else was available in the ice cream maker arena, I gave it a shot.  I was pleasantly surprised when after about 25-30 minutes of spinning I got ice cream that was about the consistency of soft serve.  The amazing thing was how good it tasted, especially if you knew how limited my cooking skills are.  The ice cream maker is still my favorite way to mate dessert even after a year.  Definitely worth every last dollar.A few suggestions:  Ice cream and any frozen dessert you may make freezes best if you either use chilled ingredients for recipes that involve no cooking, and when they do need heating it helps quite a lot to thoroughly chill the mixture to near freezing before transferring to the device.  Being a chemist, the approach I naturally took was the same as in lab: put a smaller container (mixing bowl) with the hot ice cream mixture inside a bigger container (slightly larger mixing bowl of the same shape) filled with about two or three dozen ice cubes + water.  If one stirs the mixture every few minutes, it's ready to freeze in no time.If the result of the ice cream maker is not solid enough in the suggested freezing time of 20-25 minutes, I've found that letting it mix up to about a maximum of 40-45 minutes continues to harden your frozen dessert. (Coincidentally, there seems to be an auto shut-off at that same time - presumably to prevent burning out the motor) Beyond that sitting 2-3 hours in the freezer will give you completely solid ice cream.Also I suggest taking the time to try to cook a custard.  It may take more than one attempt to get it right, but if you do the treat is well worth it.  Vanilla custard is by far my favorite ice cream now and no store bought ice cream can compare!  There's a recipe for Philly soft serve that's great as well and is not as tricky (recipes for both were found in a book called Frozen Desserts by Caroline Liddell).  A friend of mine apparently found the ideal way to cook a custard with such an ice cream maker.  He apparently got his hands on an old hot plate with a magnetic stirrer that was being tossed at his lab.  He says it works great: you set the thermostat to the right number, turn on the stirrer and it maintains a constant 180 degrees Fahrenheit just like in lab.  And your custard is done cooking in 15 minutes with virtually no risk of curdling by overheating.  Now if only I could find one of those on its way to the junk yard!
